Sure, here's some code that creates a tile-like gradient wave for the background of the section:

```
<section>
  <div class="background">
    <h1>Section Title</h1>
    <p>Section content goes here</p>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  section {
    margin-bottom: 0px;
    text-align: center;
    height: 100%;
    width: 100%;
  }

  .background {
    background: linear-gradient(-45deg, #5FB548, #A6D608 25%, transparent 25%, transparent 50%, #A6D608 50%, #A6D608 75%, transparent 75%, transparent);
    background-size: 200% 200%;
    animation: wave 10s ease-in-out infinite;
    color: white;
    font-size: 18px;
    font-weight: bold;
    padding-top: 100px;
    text-shadow: 0px 2px 2px 0px #37472B;
    position: relative;
    z-index: -1;
  }

  h1, p {
    margin: 0;
  }

  @keyframes wave {
    0% {
      background-position: 0 0;
    }
    100% {
      background-position: -200% -200%;
    }
  }
</style>
```

This uses a technique called CSS gradient animation to create a tiled wave-like gradient as the background for the section. The `background` property creates the gradient, with the transparent sections creating the tile effect. The `background-size` property sets the size of the tiled areas. The `animation` property sets the wave animation, with the keyframe animation moving the background position from 0 to -200% to create the wave effect. The `position` and `z-index` properties layer the background behind the text content. Finally, the `h1` and `p` styles remove any default margin from these elements.

