Certainly, here's an updated style code that creates a horizontally tileable gradient wave background using CSS3 gradient background images:

```
html {
  height: 100%;
}

body {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  margin: 0;
  min-height: 100%;
  background-image: linear-gradient(-60deg, #5FB548, #A6D608 40%, #A6D608 60%, #5FB548);
  background-size: 180% 100%;
  background-repeat: repeat-x;
  animation: wave 10s ease-in-out infinite;
}

section {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  margin-top: -35px;
  padding-top: 35px;
  height: 100%;
}

@keyframes wave {
  0% {
    background-position: 0% 0%;
  }
  100% {
    background-position: 100% 0%;
  }
}
```

The `background-image` is set to a linear gradient with four color stops that transition between the two shades of green that you've used previously. By setting the `background-size` to 180% x 100% we create a repeating pattern for the gradient background that will seamlessly transition into a new copy of itself as it repeats horizontally. `background-repeat` is set to `repeat-x` to allow the pattern to repeat only horizontally. The animation is set using the `@keyframes` rule which shifts the background position over the duration of 10 seconds.

Also, each section uses `display: flex` to align content vertically using `justify-content: center;` and `align-item: center;`, while adding negative margin to make the wave pattern start just under each section's text content.

Feel free to adjust the color stops and timing of the wave animation as needed to fit your project's style.

