Sure, here's an example of how you might make the text more readable on the gradient wave background:

```
<section class="gradient-wave">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Section Title</h1>
    <p>Section content goes here</p>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .gradient-wave {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    margin-top: -35px;
    padding-top: 35px;
    height: 100%;
    background-image: linear-gradient(-60deg, #5FB548, #A6D608 40%, #A6D608 60%, #5FB548);
    background-size: 180% 100%;
    background-repeat: repeat-x;
    animation: wave 10s ease-in-out infinite;
  }

  .container {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    text-shadow: 1px 1px #000000;
  }

  h1, p {
    margin: 0;
    color: white;
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 2rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  @keyframes wave {
    0% {
      background-position: 0% 0%;
    }
    100% {
      background-position: 100% 0%;
    }
  }
</style>
```

In this example, we've added a container `div` around the text elements, which we've styled with a `position` of `relative` and a `z-index` of `1` to place it above the gradient wave background. We've also added a `text-shadow` to the container to make the text more legible. In addition, each of the text elements is styled to have a light text color and a `text-align` center. The `font-size` and `line-height` properties can be adjusted as needed to ensure readability at different screen sizes.

Finally, we've updated the CSS animation to ensure that the gradient wave background doesn't interfere with readability. By having the wave progression occur at a slower pace than the animation speed of the text container, it allows the text to remain legible and unfazed by the waving background. Feel free to adjust the timing to achieve a good balance between readability and animation.

Sure! To add an opacity to the gradient wave background, you can use the `rgba()` function in CSS. The fourth argument to this function specifies the opacity as a value between 0 and 1, with 0 indicating complete transparency and 1 indicating complete opacity. Here's an example of how you might modify the `background-image` property in the gradient wave section style to make it semi-transparent:

```
.gradient-wave {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  margin-top: -35px;
  padding-top: 35px;
  height: 100%;
  background-image: linear-gradient(-60deg, rgba(95, 181, 72, 0.7), rgba(166, 214, 8, 0.7) 40%, rgba(166, 214, 8, 0.7) 60%, rgba(95, 181, 72, 0.7));
  background-size: 180% 100%;
  background-repeat: repeat-x;
  animation: wave 10s ease-in-out infinite;
}
```

In this example, we've set the color stops for the gradient wave background using the `rgba()` function for the two shades of green. The fourth argument to each `rgba()` function sets the opacity to 0.7, creating a semi-transparent effect for the gradient wave. Feel free to adjust the color values and opacity as needed to achieve the desired effect.
